_.k2/`W[8ClZ/zE/k9wv.text: The animation code in the _AnimateTiles block is empty for no animation, but otherwise follows this format:1st character = Animation speed in frames 1 to 9 All the following digits (0-9's) represent a single frames of the animation and are offsets from the original costume.For example: "501234321" would change animation costume once every 5 frames, and would go through the sequence +0, +1, +2, +3, +4, +3, +2, +1 and then back to +0 again looping around forever.

Each clone will remember it's x & y value at the point it was clones as these are not 'global' variables, but local to each sprite.

1Vg:j+;[:N9O8Vj!Rb=Q.text:
The "Tiles" sprite - This is where things get a little more exciting! How do we scroll around a level consiting of 1000's of tiles when we have a 300 clone limit and also keep it running smoothly? My best approach is this, to only create enough actual tile clones to fill the game play window . Each tile 'is' moved around relative to SCROLL_X and SCROLL_Y as you would expect, but when one moves outside the game play window, it is moved to the opersite side of the window and reused for the incoming tiles scrolling into view. This means we do not have to keep creating and deleting clones, and we only need to change costumes when a tile moves off screen.

1) Create a grid of "Tiles" sprite clones to fill the game play window.
2) The main game loop issues the "animate" broadcast and each of the tiles is then responsible for updating itself:
3) We first check whether the tile clone will have moved fully outside the game play window (red rectangle in this case).
     If it has, then we need to quickly move it to the opersite edge of the game play window and change it's costume to
     reflect what is about to scroll into view on that side.
4) Now we move the position of the tile based on the SCROLL_X and SCROLL_Y variables.
